## Diagnosis

The treemap tile label renderer uses a single, unconditional vertical (column) layout—label text on top, count badge below—regardless of the tile's actual pixel dimensions. When a leaf node receives a very small width allocation (≈20 px), the text overflows horizontally, the count badge is pushed below the visible area, and the whole composition looks broken. The component never queries the tile's bounding box before choosing a layout strategy.

---

## Root Cause

**AP-072 – Rigid Layout Assumption / Missing Responsive-Container Logic**

The tile content is rendered with a static flex-column stack. There is no branch that says:

> "if this tile is too narrow for a column stack, collapse to an icon-only or rotated label, or suppress the label entirely."

The component assumes the treemap algorithm will always produce tiles wide enough for the label, which is false for small-value leaf nodes.

---

## Fix

### 1. Derive a "shape class" from the tile's `width` and `height` props

Every D3 treemap layout passes `x0 / y0 / x1 / y1` (or width/height) to each tile. Use those to classify the tile before rendering.

```ts
// src/components/Treemap/TileLabel.tsx  (or wherever tile content lives)

type ShapeClass = 'wide' | 'square' | 'sliver-tall' | 'sliver-wide' | 'tiny';

function classifyTile(width: number, height: number): ShapeClass {
  const MIN = 48; // px threshold below which text is not useful
  if (width < MIN && height < MIN) return 'tiny';
  if (width < MIN) return 'sliver-tall';   // tall narrow stripe
  if (height < MIN) return 'sliver-wide';  // wide short stripe
  const ratio = width / height;
  if (ratio > 1.6) return 'wide';
  return 'square';
}
```

### 2. Map each shape class to a layout strategy

```tsx
// src/components/Treemap/TileLabel.tsx

import { classifyTile } from './classifyTile';

interface TileLabelProps {
  label: string;
  count: number;
  width: number;
  height: number;
}

export function TileLabel({ label, count, width, height }: TileLabelProps) {
  const shape = classifyTile(width, height);

  /* ── tiny: nothing fits, render nothing ─────────────────────── */
  if (shape === 'tiny') return null;

  /* ── tall-sliver: rotate the label 90°, hide count ──────────── */
  if (shape === 'sliver-tall') {
    return (
      <div
        className="absolute inset-0 flex items-center justify-center overflow-hidden"
        aria-label={`${label} (${count})`}
      >
        <span
          className="text-[10px] font-medium leading-none whitespace-nowrap text-ellipsis overflow-hidden"
          style={{ writingMode: 'vertical-rl', transform: 'rotate(180deg)' }}
        >
          {label}
        </span>
      </div>
    );
  }

  /* ── wide-sliver: single line, label + count side-by-side ────── */
  if (shape === 'sliver-wide') {
    return (
      <div className="absolute inset-0 flex items-center gap-1 px-1.5 overflow-hidden">
        <span className="text-[10px] font-medium truncate flex-1 min-w-0">
          {label}
        </span>
        <span className="text-[9px] text-foreground/60 shrink-0">{count}</span>
      </div>
    );
  }

  /* ── square / wide: original column stack (safe dimensions) ──── */
  return (
    <div className="absolute inset-0 flex flex-col items-start justify-end gap-0.5 p-2 overflow-hidden">
      <span className="text-xs font-semibold leading-tight line-clamp-2 min-w-0">
        {label}
      </span>
      <span className="text-[10px] text-foreground/60">{count}</span>
    </div>
  );
}
```

### 3. Pass actual pixel dimensions into each tile

In the parent treemap node renderer, compute width/height from the D3 coordinates:

```tsx
// src/components/Treemap/TreemapNode.tsx

export function TreemapNode({ node }: { node: HierarchyRectangularNode<Datum> }) {
  const width  = node.x1 - node.x0;
  const height = node.y1 - node.y0;

  return (
    <g transform={`translate(${node.x0},${node.y0})`}>
      <rect width={width} height={height} className="fill-surface stroke-background" />
      {/* ↓ explicit pixel dimensions, not percentages or CSS auto */}
      <foreignObject width={width} height={height}>
        <TileLabel
          label={node.data.name}
          count={node.data.count}
          width={width}
          height={height}
        />
      </foreignObject>
    </g>
  );
}
```

### 4. Guard against overflow at the SVG level

Add `overflow: hidden` on each `<foreignObject>` so that text from a neighbour tile can never bleed across:

```tsx
<foreignObject
  width={width}
  height={height}
  style={{ overflow: 'hidden' }}   // SVG attribute alone isn't enough in all browsers
>
```

---

## Decision table (quick reference)

| width | height | shape class | label strategy |
|-------|--------|-------------|---------------|
| < 48 px | < 48 px | `tiny` | render nothing |
| < 48 px | ≥ 48 px | `sliver-tall` | rotated vertical text, no count |
| ≥ 48 px | < 48 px | `sliver-wide` | truncated single-line row |
| ≥ 48 px | ≥ 48 px | `square` / `wide` | original column stack |

---

## Principle

**Content must adapt to its container; containers must not be assumed to fit their content.**

Treemap tiles are allocated by a space-partitioning algorithm that has no knowledge of label widths. The label renderer—not the layout algorithm—must inspect available space at render time and degrade gracefully through a hierarchy of display strategies: full label + count → abbreviated → rotated → suppressed. This is the same progressive-disclosure contract used by responsive data-visualisation libraries (e.g., Observable Plot's `tip`, Recharts' `label` with `overflow: hidden`). Omitting it is **AP-072**.
